● Here's what /sk-backfill-claudebeat does:

  Purpose: Retrospectively fill in diary articles for dates before the earliest
  existing entry. You give it a start date, it writes everything from that date up to
   (but not including) the oldest article already in the repo.

  Invocation: /sk-backfill-claudebeat 2026-02-01 — replace the date with wherever you
   want to start from.

  Key rules that make it different from the normal daily skill:

  - No future knowledge — each article is written as if on that date. No hints, no
  outcomes, no forward references.
  - retrospective tag — every entry gets this tag so readers know it was written
  after the fact.
  - Placed at the bottom of the index list and SEARCH_INDEX array (not the top),
  keeping newest-first order intact for regular entries.
  - Artist ordering — new motif functions are inserted chronologically before the
  existing ones in the DAYS list.
  - One commit at the end covering all dates in the run.

  Typical use case: you decide the site should go back to, say, 1 February 2026 — you
   run /sk-backfill-claudebeat 2026-02-01 and it fills in every missing day from then
   up to wherever the earliest existing article is.

